HEADWORD: Poll
<hw>Poll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Polly</ets>,
The proper name.]</ety> <def>A parrot; -- familiarly so
called.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Poll
<hw>Poll</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ the many, the rabble.]</ety>
<def>One who does not try for honors, but is content to take a degree
merely; a passman.</def> <mark>[Cambridge Univ., Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Poll
<hw>Poll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to LG.
<ets>polle</ets> the head, the crest of a bird, the top of a tree, OD.
<ets>pol</ets>, <ets>polle</ets>, Dan. <ets>puld</ets> the crown of a
hat.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The head; the back part of the head.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧All flaxen was his <xex>poll</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A number or aggregate of heads; a list or register
of heads or individuals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are the greater <qex>poll</qex>, and in true fear⟦br⟧
They gave us our demands.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The muster file, rotten and sound, upon my life, amounts not to
fifteen thousand <qex>poll</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Specifically, the register of the names of electors
who may vote in an election.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The casting or recording of the votes of registered
electors; <as>as, the close of the <ex>poll</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All soldiers quartered in place are to remove . . . and not to
return till one day after the <qex>poll</qex> is ended.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The place where the votes are cast
or recorded; <as>as, to go to the <ex>polls</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The broad end of a hammer; the but of an
ax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European chub. See
<er>Pollard</er>, 3 <sd>(a)</sd>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Poll book</b></col>, <cd>a register of persons entitled
to vote at an election.</cd> -- <col><b>Poll evil</b></col>
<fld>(Far.)</fld>, <cd>an inflammatory swelling or abscess on a horse's
head, confined beneath the great ligament of the neck.</cd> --
<col><b>Poll pick</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>a pole having a
heavy spike on the end, forming a kind of crowbar.</cd> -- <col><b>Poll
tax</b></col>, <cd>a tax levied by the head, or poll; a capitation
tax.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Poll
<hw>Poll</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Polled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Polling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To remove the poll or
head of; hence, to remove the top or end of; to clip; to lop; to shear;
<as>as, to <ex>poll</ex> the head; to <ex>poll</ex> a
tree.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he [Absalom] <qex>pollled</qex> his head.</q> <rj><qau>2 Sam.
xiv. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His death did so grieve them that they <qex>polled</qex>
themselves; they clipped off their horse and mule's hairs.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. North.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cut off; to remove by clipping, shearing, etc.;
to mow or crop; -- sometimes with <xex>off</xex>; <as>as, to
<ex>poll</ex> the hair; to <ex>poll</ex> wool; to <ex>poll</ex>
grass.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who, as he <qex>polled</qex> off his dart's head, so sure he had
decreed⟦br⟧
That all the counsels of their war he would <qex>poll</qex> off like
it.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To extort from; to plunder; to strip.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which <qex>polls</qex> and pills the poor in piteous wise.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To impose a tax upon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To pay as one's personal tax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The man that <qex>polled</qex> but twelve pence for his head.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To enter, as polls or persons, in a list or
register; to enroll, esp. for purposes of taxation; to enumerate one by
one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Polling</qex> the reformed churches whether they equalize in
number those of his three kingdoms.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To register or deposit, as a vote; to elicit or call
forth, as votes or voters; <as>as, he <ex>polled</ex> a hundred votes
more than his opponent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>poll</qex> for points of faith his trusty vote.</q>
<rj><qau>Tickell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To cut or shave smooth or even; to
cut in a straight line without indentation; <as>as, a <ex>polled</ex>
deed</as>. See <er>Dee<?/ poll</er>.</def>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 9. to inquire (of a group of persons) to learn their opinion on
some subject. Similar to poll a jury, but often used to determine the
opinions of a group by polling a portion of that group. Thus, opinion
poll. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To poll a jury</b></col>, <cd>to call upon each member of
the jury to answer individually as to his concurrence in a verdict which
has been rendered.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Poll
<hw>Poll</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To vote at an election.</def>
<rj><au>Beaconsfield.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pollack</ent>⟦br⟧
